        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We aim to detect dust continuum emission from star-forming galaxies in a rich cluster at z=1.237 with Band 7 observations.

We request single pointings of five fields that are within a few arcminutes of each other. Each pointing is centered on one of the primary targets. There are several additional, ancillary targets that will fall within each field. The targets are all on order 1'' in size.

Band 7 is most appropriate for this detection because the shape of the dust SED is approximately S_nu ~ nu^{3.8} (Dunne &amp; Eales 2001; Clements, Dunne, &amp; Eales 2009). At 350 GHz, the observations will measure rest-frame ~390um emission, which is well-suited to detection dust continuum emission. We plan to use the full 7.5GHz bandwidth to maximize sensitivity.

The star formation rates are ~3 Msun/yr based on the [OII] 3727A line (Demarco et al. 2007). We have scaled the SFRs and molecular gas masses measured by Tacconi et al. (2010) at z~1 to estimate M_mol ~3x10^9 Msun for our sample.  We then used the molecular gas masses and submm luminosities for local star forming galaxies (Scoville et al. 2012) to estimate the observed 350 GHz fluxes at z=1.2 with the assumption that the SED shape is S_nu ~ nu^{3.8}. This calculation indicates that a galaxy with 10^9 Msun of molecular gas at z=1.2 should have an observed-frame 350 GHz flux of 0.15 mJy. We request a continuum rms sensitivity of 0.05 mJy to obtain 3-sigma detections.  This should be a conservative detection criterion because [OII] luminosities often underestimate the true star formation rates, potentially by up to an order of magnitude (and thus we have underestimated the cold ISM mass and continuum luminosities).  The ALMA ETC indicates that an rms continuum sensitivity of 0.05 mJy will require approximately 16.5 minutes per pointing for the default observing conditions. Our total time request is 3 hours with overheads and calibrations.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
