    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The evolution of the cold ISM in cluster galaxies, and how the cluster environment shuts down star formation over cosmic time, are important questions because massive cluster galaxies represent the descendants of higher-redshift quasars and should begin to fall below the starforming-galaxy main sequence by z~1. We request Band 7 continuum observations to conduct a pilot study of nine galaxies in a massive cluster at z=1.237 to study the cold ISM at this important epoch. We will use these data to measure dust masses, derive the molecular gas masses, determine the molecular gas fractions, and quantify obscured star formation in cluster galaxies. The cluster RDCS J1252.9-2927 is the best, first target for this study because of its mass (5e14 Msun), substantial membership and ancillary data, and declination. We propose to observe four actively star-forming members and five relatively passive members (plus four field galaxies at a similar redshift) with only five pointings. We will use this sample to study the relative properties of the cold ISM in clusters and the field at z~1. We will also compare to cluster and field samples in the local universe and high-redshift protoclusters.</prp:abstract>
